Warning/Info Notifications:
Use brand-warning (orange) for warnings.
Use a neutral grey or blue for informational messages.
Adapt background, border, text colours, and icons accordingly.
6. Iconography & Imagery
Icons:
Use a clean, modern icon set (e.g., Heroicons, Feather Icons, or custom SVG icons).
Style with text-brand-dark, text-brand-white, or text-brand-red for accents.
Ensure icons are visually balanced with your bold typography.
Imagery:
High-quality, crisp images are essential, following Apple's lead.
Ensure images are well-composed and fit the minimalist aesthetic.
Use images with clear subjects and uncluttered backgrounds.
7. Interaction States
Crucial for usability.

Hover: Provide clear visual feedback.
Buttons: Darken background (e.g., bg-brand-red to bg-brand-red-dark).
Links: Change colour or add/remove underline (hover:text-brand-red-dark hover:underline).
Cards/Interactive elements: Subtle lift (e.g., hover:shadow-xl hover:-translate-y-1 transition-all duration-200 ease-in-out).
Focus: Use highly visible focus rings, especially for keyboard navigation.
Tailwind's default focus:ring-2 focus:ring-offset-2 is a good start. Customize the ring colour to focus:ring-brand-red or a suitable contrasting colour.
Active: Indicate when an element is pressed.
Buttons: Slightly darker background or inset shadow. active:bg-brand-red-dark or active:scale-95 transition-transform duration-75.
Disabled: Clearly indicate non-interactivity.
opacity-50 cursor-not-allowed. Ensure text contrast remains acceptable.
8. Accessibility Notes
Colour Contrast: Your primary white/dark palette should provide excellent contrast. However, pay close attention to:
text-brand-grey-medium on various backgrounds.
Red text (text-brand-red) on white/light backgrounds. Ensure it's bold enough or large enough if it doesn't meet AA contrast for normal text.
Use tools to check contrast ratios (WCAG AA minimums: 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text).
Focus States: Essential for keyboard users. Don't remove outlines without providing a clear alternative.
Semantic HTML: Use appropriate HTML tags (<nav>, <button>, <main>, etc.) to provide structure for assistive technologies.
Alt Text: Provide descriptive alt text for all meaningful images.
9. Tailwind CSS Configuration Tips (tailwind.config.js)
Recap of key tailwind.config.js extensions:

JavaScript

// tailwind.config.js
const defaultTheme = require('tailwindcss/defaultTheme');

module.exports = {
  content: [
    "./src/**/*.{html,js,jsx,ts,tsx}", // Adjust to your project structure
  ],
  theme: {
    extend: {
      colors: {
        'brand-white': '#FFFFFF',
        'brand-near-white': '#F7F7F7',
        'brand-dark': '#1A1A1A',
        'brand-near-dark': '#2C2C2C',
        'brand-red': '#FF3B30',      // Or your preferred red
        'brand-red-dark': '#D63027',
        'brand-grey-light': '#E5E5EA',
        'brand-grey-medium': '#8E8E93',
        'brand-grey-dark': '#3A3A3C',
        'brand-success': '#34C759',
        'brand-warning': '#FF9500',
      },
      fontFamily: {
        sans: ['Inter', ...defaultTheme.fontFamily.sans],
        // mono: ['YourMonoFont', ...defaultTheme.fontFamily.mono],
      },
      // You can also extend spacing, borderRadius, etc. if needed
      // borderRadius: {
      //   'xl': '0.75rem', // Apple often uses slightly more rounded corners
      //   '2xl': '1rem',
